This is a known breaking change. Android 15 (API 35) enforces edge-to-edge rendering, which makes `SOFT_INPUT_ADJUST_RESIZE` a no-op. .NET 10 MAUI targets this API level.

The modern replacement is **`WindowInsetsCompat`** — you listen for IME (keyboard) insets and adjust your layout's bottom padding yourself.

**1. Remove the old API call** — delete any `WindowSoftInputModeAdjust.Resize` usage.

**2. Ensure your manifest still has `adjustResize`** (in `Platforms/Android/AndroidManifest.xml`):

```xml
<activity … android:windowSoftInputMode="adjustResize" />
```

**3. Add a helper that listens for keyboard insets** (e.g., `Platforms/Android/KeyboardInsetHandler.cs`):

```csharp
#if ANDROID
using Android.Views;
using AndroidX.Core.View;
using Microsoft.Maui.Platform;

namespace YourApp.Platforms.Android;

public static class KeyboardInsetHandler
{
    public static void Attach(View rootView, Microsoft.Maui.Controls.View mauiBottomBar)
    {
        ViewCompat.SetOnApplyWindowInsetsListener(rootView, new InsetListener(mauiBottomBar));
    }

    private class InsetListener(Microsoft.Maui.Controls.View bottomBar)
        : Java.Lang.Object, IOnApplyWindowInsetsListener
    {
        public WindowInsetsCompat OnApplyWindowInsets(View v, WindowInsetsCompat insets)
        {
            var ime = insets.GetInsets(WindowInsetsCompat.Type.Ime());
            var nav = insets.GetInsets(WindowInsetsCompat.Type.NavigationBars());

            // ime.Bottom is the keyboard height in px; subtract the nav bar
            // so you don't double-pad when the keyboard is closed.
            var keyboardPx = Math.Max(ime.Bottom - nav.Bottom, 0);
            var density = v.Context!.Resources!.DisplayMetrics!.Density;

            bottomBar.Margin = new Microsoft.Maui.Thickness(0, 0, 0, keyboardPx / density);
            return insets;
        }
    }
}
#endif
```

**4. Wire it up in your chat page:**

```csharp
public partial class ChatPage : ContentPage
{
    protected override void OnAppearing()
    {
        base.OnAppearing();

#if ANDROID
        var activity = Platform.CurrentActivity!;
        var rootView = activity.Window!.DecorView.FindViewById(Android.Resource.Id.Content)!;
        Platforms.Android.KeyboardInsetHandler.Attach(rootView, InputBar);
#endif
    }
}
```

Where `InputBar` is whatever `Grid`/`HorizontalStackLayout` holds your `Entry` + Send button at the bottom.

**Why this works:** Instead of the OS resizing your window (the old behavior), you're explicitly reading the keyboard's pixel height from the inset system and translating it into a bottom margin. This is the mechanism Android 15+ expects apps to use.

> **Tip:** On iOS this isn't needed — MAUI's `KeyboardAutoManagerScroll` (on by default since .NET 8) already handles it. If you ever need to disable it per-page: `KeyboardAutoManagerScroll.Disconnect();`.
